  @{b}- Distribution -@{ub} 

AnArchiver is Freeware, this means that it may be freely distributed as long
as no more than a nominal fee is charged to cover time and copying costs.
Everything in this distribution must be kept together, in original unmodified
form.



  @{b}- XADmaster Info -@{ub}

AnArchiver uses Dirk Stoecker's XADmaster system which strictly speaking still
is Shareware, but since he no longer accepts any new registrations, it means
that you can get it for free. Just download the free keyfile from Aminet.









@endnode


@node Requirements

  @{b}- Requirements -@{ub}

AnArchiver requires the following:

  *  Amiga with OS 3.0 or higher.

  *  030 processor or higher + some Fast Ram is recommended.

  *  High Res Laced type of Workbench screenmode (with 1:1 pixel ratio).

  *  Dirk Stoecker's XADmaster system installed on your system.

  *  Mirko Thoele's "Count" command installed in C:

The above is what you need to get AnArchiver working, but you will of course
also need the actual Archivers to be able to do something useful, included
in the "C" drawer of the AnArchiver distribution are the following files:

   -  LhA    V1.38
   -  LZX    V1.21 (68020 version)
   -  Zip    V2.2
   -  UnZip  V5.32
   -  LZX.Keyfile  (generic keyfile)

These are the versions that I use, so AnArchiver was made with that in mind.
I'm not sure if it will work with other versions of these files (there are
problems with LhA V2.1 for example).

I was not sure about whether I should include these files in the AnArchiver
distribution or not, since the makers of these programs clearly states in
their documentation that all files must be included with the Archivers (which
mainly consists of docs). If I did this, the AnArchiver distribution would
have been much larger than it is now.

But I know from personal experience how annoying it is to download some
software, only to find out that it also requires some other files which are
not included. So I decided to only include the files which are needed in this
distribution. I hope that it is OK to include them as long as I mention that
not all files are included and I give some information on where they can be
found.

Here is where you can find them on Aminet:
  LhA   -  util/arc/LhA_e138.run
  LZX   -  util/arc/lzx121r1.lha
  Zip   -  util/arc/Zip.lha
  UnZip -  util/arc/UnZip.lha


The XADmaster system can also be found on Aminet, just download one of the
following archives that best suits your processor:
  util/arc/xadmaster000.lha
  util/arc/xadmaster020.lha
  util/arc/xadmaster060.lha

Do also download the free xadmaster keyfile:
  util/arc/xadmaster-key.lha

PS! If you have AmigaOS 3.9, xadmaster is already included. But it is really
recommended that you update to the latest version of xadmaster, this might
become a requirement in future versions of AnArchiver.


As for Count & IDer, they are both included with the AnArchiver distribution.

@endnode


@node Installation

  @{b}- Installation -@{ub}

This is really easy because the AnArchiver distribution does now include a
installation utility, just start it to install AnArchiver to your Amiga.
But if you want to install AnArchiver manually, follow the instructions that
you will  find in the "Install.readme" file  included with the  AnArchiver
distribution.

Please Note! It's not recommended that you install version 1.60 of AnArchiver
over a older version, there probably won't be any major problems in doing so,
but it WILL lead to reduntant files being present on your system.

The best thing is to make a clean install!


Another thing I would like to mention is that unlike the older versions of
the AnArchiver installer, the current one will automatically install the
AnArchiver fonts to the Fonts dir of your boot partition. The reason for this
is that the old "Assign" method would not always work like it should. But if
you simply refuse to have the AnArchiver fonts in Fonts:, just delete them
and AnArchiver will make an temporary Assign to Fonts: every time it is
started (just like before). But remember that you do this at your own risk!


Just to remind you about what other files AnArchiver requires, the following
files must exist somewhere in your command search-path (C: is recommended):

       Gui
       Gui4Cli
       LhA
       LZX
       Zip
       UnZip
       Count
       IDer (optional)

It is also recommended that you have LZX.Keyfile installed in L:

Remember that in order to use AnArchiver, you will also need Dirk Stoecker's
XADmaster system installed on your system.

@endnode


@node Important

  @{b}- Important -@{ub}

Before using AnArchiver or reading this guide, please note the following:

When referring to @{b}"Selected files and dirs"@{ub} in this guide, what is meant is
files and dirs that are selected in the @{b}_listview_@{ub} (highlighted), and when
referring to @{b}"Selected paths"@{ub} it means the @{b}path leading@{ub} to the files and dirs
in the listview (which are shown in the gadget below the lv).

All three Archivers have some functions which are similar but have different
names, so to make things easier, I had to come up with some standard names
to them. Have this in mind if you read the documentations of the Archivers.

Some of the Archivers (especially Zip) lacks some functions that I wanted
to use with AnArchiver, in those cases I had to come up with my own solutions
to compensate for this. Have this in mind if you decide to use the Archivers
in a Shell and you find out that some options seems to be missing.

@endnode


