@node MainWindowButtons "Main Window Buttons"

    @{b}- Main Window Buttons -@{ub}

On the top of the Main AnArchiver window there are seven buttons:

  @{b}- Add -@{ub}
This will open the @{"Add Files Window" link AddFilesWin} where you can select the files you
want to be added to the archive.


  @{b}- Extract -@{ub}
When you press this button, the selected files (in the listview) will be
extracted to the chosen destination directory.


  @{b}- Delete -@{ub}
By pressing this button, the selected files in the listview will be deleted
from the archive (after asking you first). If all files are selected, the
entire archive will be deleted.

Please Note! Files deleted from an archive file cannot be recovered in
any way. Once a file is deleted from an archive it is gone forever!  


  @{b}- View -@{ub}
The View button will extract and view the first of the selected files in the
listview (can also be done by double-clicking a file in the listview).
For more information, take a look at the @{"Extract & View files" link ExtractAndView} section.


  @{b}- Options -@{ub}
This will open the Options Window, where you can change various options used
by AnArchiver.


  @{b}- Iconify -@{ub}
This will Iconify AnArchiver. By double-clicking the AppIcon, AnArchiver will
be opened again. If you drag and drop an archive's icon on to the AppIcon,
AnArchiver will open with that archive selected.


  @{b}- Quit -@{ub}
Surprise, surprise, this will Quit AnArchiver.
If you have the "Ask before Quitting AnArchiver" option enabled (which can be
set in the @{"AnArchiver Settings" link SettingsWindow} Gui), you will be asked if you really want to
quit AnArchiver, this option is enabled by default.



  @{b}- Keyboard Shortcuts -@{ub}

     F1  =  Add
     F2  =  Extract
     F3  =  Delete
     F4  =  View
     F5  =  Options
     F6  =  Iconify
     F7  =  Quit

@endnode

@node Archive

    @{b}- Archive -@{ub}

Here is where you can select the archive you want to act upon, just enter the
name in the text-gadget or press the button to the far right, this will pop up
a file-requester allowing you to select an archive, or if you want to create a
new one, just enter the new file name.
Remember that you _must_ include the full path to the archive.

You can also select an archive by dragging and dropping it's icon into the
file-requester window, or when AnArchiver is Iconified, on to it's AppIcon.

The "R" button will set the archive path to Ram:.

The button next to "R" will open the archive-history window, where you can
select an archive from a list of the previously selected ones.

@endnode


@node MainWindowLV "Archive Contents Listview"

    @{b}- Archive Contents Listview -@{ub}

This listview shows the contents of the selected archive.

Here you can select the files that you want to be extracted or deleted from
the archive. This is a multi-select listview which allows you to select
multiple files, Just select the ones that you want and press the "Extract"
button to extract the files or "Delete" to delete them from the archive.

If you double-click a file in the listview, it will be extracted and viewed.
For more information, take a look at the @{"Extract & View files" link ExtractAndView} section.


The text-gadget below the listview shows the amount of selected files.
Please Note! Directory entries in the archive will count as files when
calculating the file-amount, in other words "Little/Test/" will be counted
as a file, even when it is a directory. You can find out the real amount
of files in the archive by opening the "Archive Information" window from the
Archive menu.


At the right of the text-gadget there are five navigation buttons that will
move the listview horisontally (the middle one will reset the position).


At the far right under the listview there are four buttons:

  U  -  Will Update the listview by re-reading the archive-contents.
  A  -  Will select All files in the listview.
  N  -  Will select None of the files in the listview.
  I  -  Will Invert all selections.


Please Note!  When you re-select a previously selected archive, the contents
list will always be read from the cache unless the archive has been modified
in any way. But by pressing the "U" button, the list will be read directly
from the archive again even if it's already in the cache.

@endnode

@node Dest

    @{b}- Dest -@{ub}

Here you can select the destination directory that you want the selected files
to be extracted to, just enter the name in the text-gadget or press the button
to the far right, this will pop up a requester allowing you to select a dir.
Remember that you _must_ include the full path to the selected directory.


The "R" button will set the extract directory to Ram:.


The button next to "R" will open the extract dir-history window, where you can
select a directory from a list of the previously selected ones.


Please Note!  It is possible to enter the path to a non-existing directory if
you want to, then it will be created when you start extracting files.

@endnode

@node BottomGads "Bottom Gadgets"

    @{b}- Status & Busy -@{ub}


  @{b}- Status -@{ub}
At the bottom of the AnArchiver Main window there is a text gadget which will
show you some info about what AnArchiver currently is doing (or the result of
what it was doing).


  @{b}- Busy -@{ub}
The gadget in the bottom-right corner works as a "Busy" indicator.
As you can read somewhere else in this guide, it is possible to have up to 20
AnArchiver windows running at the same time, but AnArchiver can only perform
certain actions (Add, Extract, Delete & Test) on only one archive at a time.

So when this gadget changes colour it means that AnArchiver is busy with doing
something and you have to wait for it to finish before doing anything else.

@endnode

@node MainProjectMenu "Project Menu"

    @{b}- Project Menu -@{ub}


  @{b}- About AnArchiver -@{ub}
Shows some information about AnArchiver. If you press the "More Info" button,
you will also get a list of the files used by AnArchiver.


  @{b}- XAD client information -@{ub}
Displays the name, flags, ID, required xadmaster version, version and revision
of all clients in xadmaster.library.
Meaning of the abbrevations:
    ID  - internal client ID
    MV  - required master version
    VER - client version and revision
The Flags field gives information about the different flags set in the client.


  @{b}- AnArchiver Status -@{ub}
Opens the AnArchiver Status Window. This window can give you a list over all
the currently running AnArchiver windows, it also allows you to select to
open one of them (or a new one). This window can also be opened by selecting
"AnArchiver Status" from the Workbench Tools menu.


  @{b}- New window -@{ub}
Opens a new AnArchiver window. Remember that you can only have a maximum of
20 AnArchiver windows running at the same time.


  @{b}- Output window -@{ub}
Opens the @{"Gui Output Window" link OutputWindow}, this is useful if you want to check what
AnArchiver was doing the last time (and the result of what it was doing).


  @{b}- Sort ListView -@{ub}
Will sort the main window listview alphabetically, in ascending order.


  @{b}- Iconify -@{ub}
This will Iconify AnArchiver. By double-clicking the AppIcon, AnArchiver will
be opened again. If you drag and drop an archive's icon on to the AppIcon,
AnArchiver will open with that archive selected.


  @{b}- Quit -@{ub}
Surprise, surprise, this will Quit AnArchiver.
If you have the "Ask before Quitting AnArchiver" option enabled (which can be
set in the @{"AnArchiver Settings" link SettingsWindow} Gui), you will be asked if you really want to
quit AnArchiver, this option is enabled by default.

@endnode

@node MainActionsMenu "Actions Menu"

    @{b}- Actions Menu -@{ub}


  @{b}- Add files -@{ub}
This will open the @{"Add Files Window" link AddFilesWin} where you can select the files you
want to be added to the archive.


  @{b}- Extract files -@{ub}
Extracts the selected files (in the listview) to the chosen destination dir.


  @{b}- Delete files -@{ub}
If you choose this, the selected files in the listview will be deleted from
the archive (after asking you first). If all files are selected, the entire
archive will be deleted.

Please Note! Files deleted from an archive file cannot be recovered in
any way. Once a file is deleted from an archive it is gone forever!  


  @{b}- Test archive -@{ub}
This will test the archive integrity by extracting the files it contains
to nowhereland, i.e. the data is decompressed only, not written to any
file. This function only works on entire archives, i.e. you cannot just
test one file in an archive. If this command fails, the archive is
corrupted, and a warning return code is returned.


  @{b}- View file -@{ub}
This will extract and view the first of the selected files in the listview
(can also be done by double-clicking a file in the listview).
For more information, take a look at the @{"Extract & View files" link ExtractAndView} section.

@endnode

@node MainArchiveMenu "Archive Menu"

    @{b}- Archive Menu -@{ub}


  @{b}- Copy archive -@{ub}
Copy the archive to the directory you select from the requester that pops up.

  @{b}- Move archive -@{ub}
Move the archive to the directory you select from the requester that pops up.

  @{b}- Rename archive -@{ub}
Rename the selected archive.

  @{b}- Delete archive -@{ub}
Delete the selected archive (after asking you first).

  @{b}- Information -@{ub}
Shows some information about the selected archive, here is an explenation:

      Name: The Name of the archive
      Path: The Path leading to the archive
      Type: The Type of archive
     Files: Amount of files in the archive @{b}*@{ub}
      Size: Total size of all the files in the archive
  CrndSize: Total compressed size of all the files in the archive
     Ratio: Compression Ratio
 File Size: Size of the archive-file
 Date/Time: The Date & Time when the archive was last modified
Protection: Protection bits of the archive-file
   Comment: File Comment of the archive (if any)


@{b}*@{ub}  Please Note! Directory entries in the archive will count as files when
calculating the file-amount, in other words "Little/Test/" will be counted
as a file, even when it is a directory. If the archive have both directory
and file entries in it, the real amount of files will be shown to the right
of the File amount number. Here is an example:

     Files: 437 (379 for real)

This means there are 437 entries in total in the archive, but only 379 of
them are files, the rest are directories.



@endnode

@node MainMiscMenu "Misc Menu"

    @{b}- Misc Menu -@{ub}


  @{b}- Search... -@{ub}
This will allow you to search for files in the selected archive (or in the
listview to be more precise), but there is however one limitation: Searching
by using wildcard characters are NOT supported.


  @{b}- Mark Icons -@{ub}
This will search for and mark all icons (files with .info extension) in the
listview. This can be useful if there are icons in a archive which is not
only intended for Amiga users, then you can mark and delete them from the
archive.


  @{b}- Mark Directories -@{ub}
Selecting this will search for and mark all directory entries in the listview.
The reason why I included this function in AnArchiver has to do with the Zip
archiver. If paths are used when adding files to a zip archive, Zip will
always create a seperate entry for EVERY directory in the archive (and there
is NO way of avoiding this). I find this to be a little annoying because while
it won't make the archive file-size that much bigger, it will make the file-
list longer.
So everytime after I have created a zip archive where paths are used in the
archive, I mark them out by using this function and then I delete them.


  @{b}- Enter Password -@{ub}
This will allow you to enter a password for extracting files from an encrypted
archive. What you enter here will not affect adding files to an archive since
encryption is not supported by the Archivers.


  @{b}- Delete Temporary files -@{ub}
If you select this, a Gui will open which will allow you to delete files that
have been temporarely extracted by AnArchiver. For more information, read the
@{"Delete Temporary Files" link DelTempFilesWin} Window section.

@endnode

@node MainHistAndCacheMenu "History & Cache Menu"

    @{b}- History & Cache Menu -@{ub}


  @{b}- Clean up archive history -@{ub}
This will clean up the archive history list by removing all "dead" archives
from the list.

  @{b}- Clean up dest history -@{ub}
This will clean up the extract-directory history list by removing all "dead"
dirs from the list.

  @{b}- Clear archive history -@{ub}
This will clear (delete) the entire archive history list.

  @{b}- Clear dest history -@{ub}
This will clear (delete) the entire extract-dir history list.

  @{b}- Clear archive cache -@{ub}
AnArchiver stores the archive contents list into a cache after it is read
from a archive, this will speed up the updating of the listview if you later
select it again. But if you have opened a lot of archives, it may use a lot
of ram (because the cache is stored on the ram disk). So if you want to free
up the ram the cache uses, you can select this. 

Please Note! The cache will automatically be deleted when you quit AnArchiver.

@endnode

@node MainSettingsMenu "Settings Menu"

    @{b}- Settings Menu -@{ub}


  @{b}- AnArchiver Options -@{ub}
This will open the @{"Options Window" link AnArchOptions}, where you can change various options used
by AnArchiver.

  @{b}- AnArchiver Settings -@{ub}
This will open the AnArchiver @{"Settings Window" link SettingsWindow} where you can configure various
things about AnArchiver.

  @{b}- IDer Settings -@{ub}
This will open the @{"IDer Settings Window" link IDerSettingsWindow} where you can configure what viewers
and players that should be used when using IDer to view/play files.

@endnode

@node MainHelpMenu "Help Menu"

    @{b}- Help Menu -@{ub}


  @{b}- Turn Gad help On/Off -@{ub}
If you turn Gad help On, take a look at at the WB screen-title while your
mouse pointer is over a button/gadget, then you will get some information
about what that button/gadget does.
This function can also be turned On/Off by pressing the Help key.


  @{b}- Enable disabled Windows -@{ub}
Sometimes when the Archivers encounters an error, they will stop working,
but they will not perform a linefeed, it's required that they do this so
that AnArchiver will know that they are finished.
The reason why AnArchiver needs to know this, is so that the disabled
windows gets enabled again.

If this happens to you, just select this menu item to turn the windows on.
But if an Archiver still is running, DON'T press any of the buttons in the
windows that was previously disabled because you may confuse AnArchiver!

It really should no longer be necessary to use this function because it is
now fixed in version 1.5 of AnArchiver (I hope). But for safety reasons, it
is still included (it will probably be removed in the next version).


  @{b}- Stop Archiver -@{ub}
This function is not supported in AnArchiver yet.


  @{b}- AnArchiver.guide -@{ub}
This will open this AmigaGuide.

@endnode



@node AddFilesWin "Add Files Window"

    @{b}- Add Files Window -@{ub}

   @{" The Listview       " link AddWindowLV}   The Add Files listview explained.
   @{" Type               " link ArchiveType}   Select type of archive (LhA, LZX or Zip).
   @{" Action             " link Action}   Add, Freshen, Update or Replace Files to/in the archive.
   @{" Compression        " link Compression}   Select the level (degree) of compression to use.
   @{" Use Paths          " link UsePaths}   Use Paths in the archive (Yes, Full or No).
   @{" Recurse Sub-dirs   " link Recurse}   Recursively collect files from subdirectories.
   @{" Add Empty dirs     " link AddEmptydirs}   Archive empty directories.
   @{" Compress All files " link CompressAF}   Attempt to compress all files, even if they already are compressed.


When you press the Start button, AnArchiver will start adding the selected
files and dirs to the archive. I will not bother with explaining the Volumes,
Parent & Cancel buttons, since I'm sure you will understand what they do  :-)



@endnode

@node AddWindowLV "Add Files Listview"

    @{b}- Add Files Listview -@{ub}

Here you can select the files that you want to add to the archive. This is
a multi-select listview which allows you to select multiple files/dirs.
Just select the ones you want and press the "Start" button, then the files
will be added to your archive.

You can also select files/dirs by dragging and dropping them into the window,
then these files will be the selected ones (you can also drag & drop files
into the main AnArchiver window), if they have icons, they will be selected
too. But remember that you can _only_ drag & drop files/dirs that are from
the _same_ source-dir.

The text-gadget below the listview shows the path to the files you select,
and this is the "Selected Path" that is often referred to in this guide.

At the right of the text-gadget there are three buttons:

  A  -  Will select All files/dirs in the listview
  N  -  Will select None of the files/dirs in the listview.
  I  -  Will Invert all selections.


Please Note! LZX will sometimes add files in several turns (meaning that it
will will be run more than one time) if you select a lot of files or the
selected files have long names. The reason for this is that there are some
limitations about how long the command line can be with the LZX Archiver.
But don't worry, everything will happen automatically, I just thought I
should mention this to avoid any confusion.

I have come up with an solution in those cases when all files/dirs in the
listview are selected, and this is to use pattern matching (#?) instead of
using all file names on the command line. Unfortunately this have a side
effect when the "Recurse Sub-dirs" option is turned off. You can read more
about it in the @{"Problems" link Problems} section.

LhA and Zip does also have this limitation about the command-line length,
but since they both support methods of avoiding this problem, they will be
run one time only, regardless of the amount of files you selected.

@endnode

@node ArchiveType "Type"

  @{b}- Type -@{ub}

This gadget allows you to select what type of archive you want to be created,
you can choose between LhA, LZX and Zip.  For information about what archive
type to use, read the @{"What Archive format to use" link Archive2Use} section.

@endnode

@node Action

  @{b}- Action -@{ub}

This allows you to select exactly how the files should be added to your
archive, the name of the functions are the same but the Archivers will do
different things on some of them.


  @{b}Add @{ub}
Obviously, this function adds a number of files to the archive. If the
specified archive does not already exist, then it will be created.
You cannot add files to an archive if these already exist in the archive.
If you attempt to do so, a warning will be issued, but the Archivers will
continue adding the other files you have specified.  

Please Note about Zip! If the selected files already exists in the archive,
they WILL be replaced (it is the same as the Replace Function).

  @{b}Freshen@{ub}
This function is used to freshen files in an archive. I.e. replace older
files in the archive with new files. This command never adds any files to
an archive, it just replaces those files that have older modification dates
than the corresponding selected files.

  @{b}Update@{ub}
As the function name implies, this function updates archives. It adds files
that are not yet in the archive and replaces existing but older files. The
last modification date for files are used to determine which file is the
newest one.  

  @{b}Replace@{ub}
This function works just like the update/add functions but replaces the
files that already exist in the archive regardless of the file modification
time.

@endnode

@node Compression

  @{b}- Compression -@{ub}

This allows you to select the level (degree) of compression to use:


  @{b}Off@{ub}
Just store all updated or added files in the archive without attempting to
compress them. Useful for making fast backups where archive size is of no
importance. It is not advisable to use this option when making archives for
distribution via modem or networks since the archive will end up much larger
than if it was compressed.  

  @{b}Low@{ub}
This is the fastest compression level, but the files added will have a low
compression.

  @{b}Medium@{ub}
This provides a fairly optimal balance between compression speed and degree
of compression, it's the best one to use in almost all cases (It is the
default compression level in all Archivers).

  @{b}High@{ub}
This is the slowest compression level, but the files added will have a high
compression, this will result in a smaller archive than by using the other
levels. It is useful if you are making archives for distribution via modem
or networks.

  @{b}Max@{ub}
This compression level is supported by LZX only, if you try to use it with
LhA or Zip, AnArchiver will use High compression instead.
This gives the best degree of compression when creating lzx archives, but it
will be at the complete and utter expense of speed and is mainly recommended
only when the absolute maximum degree of compression must be attained.
It requires that you have the LZX.Keyfile installed in L:


Please Note! The names used for compression levels are called Fast, Default
and  More Compression in the Archivers.

@endnode

@node UsePaths "Use Paths"

  @{b}- Use Paths -@{ub}

Here you can select if file paths should be used in the archive, and if so,
how much of the paths that should be used.


  @{b}Yes@{ub}
This will use file paths, but will exclude the path leading to to the
selected files and dirs (which are highlighted in the listview).

  @{b}Full@{ub}
The Full path leading to the selected files & dirs will be used, but the
Device/Volume name will not be included.

  @{b}No@{ub}
This will not use any paths at all.



If you are a little confused, here is an example.
Let's say you want to add the following to an archive: the files "Gene.iff"
and "Paul.iff" and a directory called "Alt" which contains the files
"Ace.iff" and "Gene.iff".
Imagine that the full path to these files are:
  Work:Graphics/Pictures/Gene.iff
  Work:Graphics/Pictures/Paul.iff
  Work:Graphics/Pictures/Alt/Ace.iff
  Work:Graphics/Pictures/Alt/Gene.iff

Then you select "Gene.iff", "Paul.iff" and "Alt" in the listview and add
them to the archive.

If you selected "Yes" in the "Use Paths" gadget, the files will appear like
this in the archive:
  Gene.iff
  Paul.iff
  Alt/Ace.iff
  Alt/Gene.iff

If you selected "Full", they will appear like this:
  Graphics/Pictures/Gene.iff
  Graphics/Pictures/Paul.iff
  Graphics/Pictures/Alt/Ace.iff
  Graphics/Pictures/Alt/Gene.iff

And with "No" selected, they will appear like this:
  Gene.iff
  Paul.iff
  Ace.iff

As you can see, if "No" had been selected in the "Use Paths" gadget, only one
of the "Gene.iff" files would have been included, The other one would either
have been skipped or it would have replaced the existing one (it depends on
what @{"Action" link Action} type you had selected).
Have in mind that this can happen when you are using this option.

@endnode

@node Recurse "Recurse Sub-dirs"

  @{b}- Recurse Sub-dirs -@{ub}

When this option is enabled, the Archivers will recursively collect files
from subdirectories.
In other words, if you want files in subdirectories of the selected 
directories (highlighted in the listview) added, you must set this on.

@endnode




@node AddEmptydirs "Add Empty dirs"

  @{b}- Add Empty dirs -@{ub}

If this option is enabled, the Archivers will archive all empty sub-dirs.  
It requires that you have the "Recurse Sub-dirs" option enabled.

Please Note about Zip! Empty directories will always be archived, no matter
what you select here.

@endnode




@node CompressAF "Compress All Files"

  @{b}- Compress All Files -@{ub}

Enabling this option will cause the Archivers to attempt compressing all
files, even the ones that already are compressed.  
By default, the Archivers will not attempt to compress files which are
already compressed (typically archive files or picture files in GIF or
JPEG format).
The reason why already compressed files should not be compressed is that
the number of bytes gained by this is so small that it is not worth the
time spent compressing/decompressing it.  
But on the other hand, when archive file-size is of BIG importance, you
should enable this function.

The file type is determined from the file extensions, and if you disable
this function for LhA, files ending in: .lzh .lha .zoo .zip arj .arc .dms
.wrp .lhw .zap .pak .pp .gif or .jpg will not be compressed.

For LZX the file extensions used are: AIN ARC ARJ DMS GIF HAP JPG LHA LHW
LZH LZX PAK PP RAR UC2 WRP ZAP ZIP ZOO.

For Zip: the same as LZX plus MP3 and PNG.


Please Note about Zip! It does not really have a file extensions list of 
file types which should not be compressed, this have to be specified on the
command line. If you try this in Shell and you don't want Zip trying to comp-
ress these file types, you specify it like this on the command line:

-n .ain:.arc:.arj:.dms:.gif:.hap:.jpg:.lha:.lhw:.lzh:.lzx:.pak:.pp:.rar:.uc2:.wrp:.zap:.zip:.zoo:.mp3:.png

In other words, you must use the -n option with the list of filetypes after
it, if you don't use this option, Zip will try to compress all files. 

@endnode



@node AnArchOptions "Options Window"

  @{b}- Options Window -@{ub}

   @{" ListView Options   " link LVOptions}   Configure options regarding the Main Window ListView.
   @{" Misc Options       " link MiscOptions}   Here you can configure various options.
   @{" Extract Options    " link ExtractOptions}   Various Extract related options.
   @{" Extract & View     " link ExAndViewOptions}   Options to be used when Extracting & Viewing files.

Any changes you make in this window will only be used by the AnArchiver
window it was started from (in other words, the changes will be local).

@endnode

@node LVOptions "ListView Options"

  @{b}- ListView Options -@{ub}

  @{b}- Show Files & Dirs Only -@{ub}
If you enable this option, only the Files and Directories in the archive will
be shown in the listview, All other information like file sizes, ratios and
dates will be ignored. The big advantage of this is that the updating of the
listview when reading the archive contents will be quicker.

  @{b}- Show File Comments -@{ub}
Here you can select if you want to have file comments shown in the listview.
The file comments (if any) will be shown in the far right part of the list.

  @{b}- Show Protection bits -@{ub}
If you enable this option, the protection-bits of each file will be shown,
it will appear in the far right part of the list (before the file comment).

  @{b}- Show Additional Info -@{ub}
If enabled, some additional information about each file will be shown, it
will appear right after the "Time" field in the list. This information varies
with each archive type, but it's typical that the compression method used are
shown.

  @{b}- Auto-Sort Listview -@{ub}
By enabling this, the main window listview will be sorted alphabetically, in
ascending order each time it gets updated.


Please Note!  Changes to any of these options will not take place in the
listview until it gets updated again, you can do this by pressing the "U"
button in the AnArchiver main window.

@endnode

@node MiscOptions "Misc Options"

  @{b}- Misc Options -@{ub}

  @{b}- Re-use Windows -@{ub}
If you enable this option, AnArchiver will use the same window instead of
opening a new one everytime you extract & view archives within archives.

  @{b}- Make log when Testing -@{ub}
If enabled, a log-file will be created everytime you test files in a archive.
This can be useful if it contains corrupt data, because you can then get a
overview of exactly WHICH files are corrupted.

  @{b}- LZX Delete C. -@{ub}
When you delete files from a lzx archive, it might happen that some files have
to be re-compressed. This gadget allows you to select the @{"compression" link Compression} level to
be used. If you select "Ask", you will be asked for it every time you want to
delete files from a lzx archive.


  @{b}- Output -@{ub}
Here you can select the output type to be used:

@{b}GUI Window@{ub}  This will send the output from the Archivers through a PIPE and
            then it will appear in a Gui Window. When the Archiver is finished,
            the Output Window will automatically be closed, to open it again,
            select "Output Window" from the Project menu. For more information
            read the @{"Gui Output Window" link OutputWindow} section.

@{b}CLI Window@{ub}  The output from the Archivers will appear in a standard CLI window
            and no changes will be made to it, this is the same raw output you
            get when you are running the Archivers in a Shell. The only except-
            ion is that  a few lines  will be added in the  beginning before
            starting the Archivers.  This option may be a little faster than
            the "GUI Window" one.

@{b}OFF (Quiet)@{ub} This option will suppress ALL messages from the Archivers, you
            will know that the Archiver is finished with what it was doing
            when the disabled windows gets enabled again. This option may be
            a little faster than the other ones.

Please Note! The "OFF (Quiet)" option will be ignored when you are testing
an Archive.

@endnode

@node ExtractOptions "Extract Options"

  @{b}- Extract Options -@{ub}

  @{b}- Use LhA for lha arch. -@{ub}
If you enable this option, the LhA Archiver will be used instead of XADmaster
system when extracting files from a lha archive. The reason why I implemented
this option is that LhA is more flexible than XAD when it comes to dealing 
with lha archives, it is also slightly faster. But there may be times when
using XAD instead of LhA is better because it can handle compression methods
that are unknown to the LhA Archiver.

  @{b}- Overwrite Files -@{ub}
If you enable this, already existing destination files will automatically be
overwritten. Normally you will be asked about this first.

  @{b}- Use Directory paths -@{ub}
If enabled, the directory names in the archive will be used when extracting,
otherwise they will be skipped and the files will be written directly to the
destination directory.

  @{b}- Keep Corrupt files -@{ub}
Keep corrupt and/or partially extracted files instead of deleting them.

  @{b}- Use External clients -@{ub}
Use external XADmaster clients for recognition purposes.

  @{b}- No File date info -@{ub}
Don't use the original date info that files in the archive have, use the
current date instead.

  @{b}- No File comments -@{ub}
Don't include file comments used by files in the selected archive.

  @{b}- No Protection bits -@{ub}
Don't use the original protection bits that the files in the archive have,
reset them to "----rwed" instead. Have in mind that script-files will lose
their "s" bit when enabling this option, so use it with care!

@endnode

@node ExAndViewOptions "Extract & View Options"

  @{b}- Extract & View Options -@{ub}

  @{b}- Use Xad system only -@{ub}
If you enable this option, only the XADmaster system will be used for
extracting files to be viewed, otherwise the LhA Archiver will be used
for lha archives and LZX for lzx archives.

  @{b}- Use MultiView only -@{ub}
If enabled, only MultiView will be used for viewing the temporarely
extracted files, otherwise IDer will be used instead (by using the file-
viewers that you have configured in the @{"IDer Settings" link IDerSettingsWindow} window).

@endnode



@node SettingsWindow "Settings Window"

  @{b}- Settings Window -@{ub}

Here you can configure various things about AnArchiver.

  @{b}- BG Picture -@{ub}
Here you can select the picture to be used as the background in AnArchiver's
windows, you can use any image format that you want as long as you have a
datatype for it installed on your system. The selected picture will be tiled
inside the windows. You can test it by pressing the "T" button, the picture
will then be loaded and updated in the Settings window.


  @{b}- Button Set -@{ub}
Here you can select the Button Set to be used for the Add, Extract, Delete,
View, Options, Iconify and Quit buttons in the main window of AnArchiver.
The buttons are in reality Icons that can be used as buttons in Gui4Cli
programs.


  @{b}- Ask before Quitting AnArchiver -@{ub}
If you enable this option, a requester will appear every time you try to
quit AnArchiver, asking if you really want to quit.


  @{b}- Show 'Adding/Deleting in X turns' requester -@{ub}
If you turn this option on, you will be notified every time when the adding,
extracting or deleting of files to/from the archive has to be done in more
than one turn. I have included this function to prevent users from being
confused when this happens, but when you are familiar with AnArchiver and
you understand how things works, you can turn this off (because it can be
a little annoying).


  @{b}- Work Dir -@{ub}
Here you can  specify what directory the  Archivers should  use to store
temporary files. Temporary files are created when adding files to archives,
or when updating an archive in some way (like deleting or freshening files).

The 'T:' directory is the default dir used for temporary files, only in rare
situations should you change this to another directory. One example can be
when you are working on a large archive and your Amiga is low on free Ram,
in this case it would be a good idea to set the work dir to somewhere on your
hard disk. A side effect of this is that it may cause the Archivers to work a
little slower than they would have with "T:" set as Work Dir.

Pressing the 'D' button will set the Work Dir to the default one.


  @{b}- Ignore LHAOPTS variable (LhA) -@{ub}
When this option is enabled, LhA will not try to read the defaults from the
LHAOPTS local or global environment variable (if it exists). I have included
this LhA option to avoid the possibility of AnArchiver getting confused by
options specified in this variable.

In case you are wondering about what the LHAOPTS variable does, here is a
short explanation:
Upon startup LhA looks for the environment variable `LHAOPTS' and includes
this as if it had been typed on the command line directly after the `LhA'
command name. This variable can contain things like option switches, and is
meant to make it easier and faster to use LhA in a shell.


  @{b}- Grow (append to) the specified archive (Zip) -@{ub}
Grow (append to) the specified zip archive, instead of creating a new one.
If this operation fails, Zip attempts to restore the archive to its original
state. If the restoration fails, the archive might become corrupted. This
option is ignored when there's no existing archive or when at least one
archive member must be updated or deleted.

In other words, enabling this option may make Zip work a little FASTER, but 
not enabling it is much SAFER. It's up to you what you prefer - Speed VS.
Safety.

@endnode


@node OutputWindow "Gui Output Window"

  @{b}- Gui Output Window -@{ub}

This window shows the output from the Archivers, it requires that the Output
option in the @{"Misc Options" link MiscOptions} section of the @{"AnArchiver Options" link AnArchOptions} window is set
to "GUI Window".

This window have three text gadgets:

  @{b}Top gadget@{ub}
This gadget shows what the Archiver currently is doing and what archive file
it is working on. Please note! this gadget doesn't get reset after the
Archiver is finished.

  @{b}Middle gadget@{ub}
Shows what file that is currently being added, extracted, deleted or tested
to/from/in the archive.

  @{b}Bottom gadget@{ub}
This one shows the result of the file that was added, extracted, deleted or
tested. Some functions of the Archivers does not make any relevant output that
could be updated in this gadget, if nothing is shown in this gadget while the
Archiver is working, it is an indication that everything went fine with the
file it was processing.


Between the top and middle text gadget there is a gauge, the purpose of it is
to show you the progress of the archive processing, when it reaches 100 % it
means that the Archiver is finished with what it was doing.

The Close button closes the Output window, you can bring it up again by
selecting "Output Window" from the Project menu in the AnArchiver main Gui.

On each side of the Close button there is a gauge. Every time a file is
added, extracted, deleted or tested to/from/in the archive they will grow
by 10 %. When they reach 100 %, they will be reset and then the growing
starts all over again.

@endnode

@node DelTempFilesWin "Delete Temporary Files Window"

  @{b}- Delete Temporary Files Window -@{ub}

This window allows you to delete files that are temporarely extracted.

When ever you want view files that are located within archives, they need to
be extracted first. Usually these files will automatically be deleted when
you are finished with them, but there are some exceptions. One of them are
archives since they will not be automatically deleted. So if you want to
clean up a little by deleting these files, you can use this window.

For more information, read the @{"Extract & View files" link ExtractAndView} section.


The cycler gadget allows you to select between files extracted to your Ram
Disk and your Hard Disk, the directories these temporary files are extracted
to are by default Ram:T/AnArchiver and Sys:T/AnArchiver. 

By pressing the Delete button, the deleting of the files will start. Please
note that this will happen without asking you first!

By pressing the Status button, you will get some info about the amount of
files and dirs that are located in the CURRENT directory. You will also get
some info about the amount of space that they occupy (in Bytes).


Please Note! All temporarely extracted files will be deleted when you quit
AnArchiver (or if several AnArchiver Guis are running, when the last one
is quit).

@endnode

@node IDerSettingsWindow "IDer Settings Window"

  @{b}- IDer Settings Window -@{ub}

Here you can configure what Viewers and Players IDer should use when you want
to view or play various types of files.

  @{b}- Categories -@{ub}
The file types are split into three main categories:

 @{b}Images@{ub}  This category includes various types of images and videos. You might
         wonder about the reason why I have included BMP since there does not
         exist a Viewer with built-in BMP support (afaik). Well the reason is
         simple, I'm tired of viewing BMP pictures with MultiView, and I think
         that using a Viewer with datatypes support (like Visage) is better.

 @{b}Sounds@{ub}  The Sounds  category  includes  various  types of  samples and music
         related formats.
         
 @{b}Other@{ub}   In this category you will find various file types that does not fit
         into any of the two other categories. At the bottom there is a type
         called Default, here you configure the Viewer to be used when  the
         file type of the file to be viewed is unknown, in other words it acts
         as a last resort before giving up. The Default Viewer is MultiView.

  @{b}- Command -@{ub}
Here you can select the command/program to be used for viewing/playing a file
by entering the name of the command into the text gadget, or you can press the
button next to it for selecting the command by using a file requester.

  @{b}- Arguments -@{ub}
Some commands/programs requires the use of arguments, and as an example I can
take AWeb-II. If you want to use it for HTML files, you must use the LOCAL
argument. Other commands does not require the use of arguments, but they can
still be used for making sure that things are done the way YOU prefer.
Read the documentation that follows the commands/programs that you want to use
in order to get some info about what arguments to use.
If you want to make sure that the command you use are quiet and does not give
any output (prints the result to the screen), you can use the >NIL: argument.

  @{b}- E/D -@{ub}
This will Enable/Disable the filetype. If you disable it, IDer will not use
it when it checks the filetype of the file to be viewed. You can use this on
file types that you are sure you will never come across. 


All the file types are by default set to MultiView, I know that this is a bit
ackward since you then will need a datatype for each file type. I will change
this in the next version of AnArchiver by giving you some suggestions about
what Viewers/Players that could be used.

@endnode













@node StartingAnArchiver "Starting AnArchiver"

  @{b}- Starting AnArchiver -@{ub}

This section describes how to start AnArchiver.

  @{b}- Starting from Workbench -@{ub}
Just double-click the AnArchiver icon. Remember that if you change the icon
to another one, the Default Tool of the new icon MUST be set to "Gui".


  @{b}- Starting from Shell -@{ub}
You can start AnArchiver in a Shell by typing "Gui AnArchiver". This has one
limitation, you can't give the name of a archive as an argument, in other
words, typing "Gui AnArchiver Ram:Kiss.lha" is not possible.

To solve this limitation, I have created a small script-file which you can
use instead, this is called "AnArchiver-Start" and is located in the main
directory of AnArchiver. To use it, enter "AnArchiver-Start Ram:Kiss.lha"
in a Shell.

There are however one little problem, the script NEEDS to know where to find
AnArchiver. This is not a problem if it has previously been started since
the assign used by AnArchiver already have been made (AnArchiver now uses an
assign which will be created the first time you start it after booting).

There are two methods the script will try to use for solving this problem:

1. First it will try to read the path to AnArchiver from the AnArchiver
settings file (Env:AnArchiver.prefs), this is because the path to AnArchiver
will automatically be included every time you save the settings.

2. If this was not successful, it will try to use the current path instead.
Just remember that you MUST CD to the AnArchiver directory first in order
for this to work.

@endnode

@node MakingNewArchive "Making A New Archive"

  @{b}- Making A New Archive -@{ub}

This section describes how to make a new archive.

It is easy to create a new archive, all you have to do is to enter the name
of a non-existing file (including the FULL path) in the "Archive" gadget
located in the AnArchiver main window. After you have done this, the bottom
text gadget should say "The file does not exist". Remember that your new 
archive will first be created when you start adding files to it.

Please note that unless you include a correct extension to the file name (so
that the name ends with either .lha .lzx or .zip), the archive type used will
be the one selected in the "Add Files Window". The correct extension will also
automatically be added to the file name when you start adding files to the
archive.

@endnode

@node ExtractAndView "Extract & View files"

  @{b}- Extract & View files -@{ub}

It is possible to view files that are located in archives, this does however
require that the files are temporarely extracted first. How all this is done
is described in this section.

You can do this by double-clicking a file in the listview located in the main
AnArchiver window. It can also be done by clicking the View button, selecting
"View File" from the Actions menu or by pressing the F4 key. This will extract
and view the first of the selected files in the listview.


  @{b}- Extracting the file -@{ub}
AnArchiver will use the following rule for deciding the location where the
file should be extracted to: The default directory is Ram:T/AnArchiver, but
if it will use more than 2/3 of your currently free total RAM, it will be
extracted to SYS:T/AnArchiver instead (where SYS: is your boot-partition).

The file will actually be extracted into a sub-dir of these directories, this
sub-dir will either be called Dir1, Dir2, Dir3, etc. The reason for this is
to allow having several files which have the same name temporarely extracted.


  @{b}- Viewing the file -@{ub}
First AnArchiver will do some internal checking of the file type:

 *  If the file is an archive, it will either become the currently selected
    one in the AnArchiver Gui it was extracted from, or a new AnArchiver Gui
    will be loaded (it depends on if "Re-use Windows" is enabled or not in
    the @{"Misc Options" link MiscOptions} section in the @{"AnArchiver Options" link AnArchOptions} window).

 *  If the file turns out to be an Icon, AnArchiver will use it's built-in
    Icon Viewer to view it. Please note that if you are using AmigaOS 3.5 or
    3.9 this viewer may not be able to view Icons of the NewIcon standard
    (only the OldIcon will be viewed). Likewise if you are using AmigaOS 3.0
    or 3.1, ColorIcons can't be viewed.

 *  If the file seems to be a library or device driver (based upon the file
    extension),  AnArchiver will check  the version of it and  display the
    result in the main AnArchiver window.

 *  If it might be a G4C program, you will be asked if you want to run or
    check the version of it (I will advice you to be careful about running
    it though).

 *  If it seems to be an executable, you will be asked about whether you
    want to run the file or check the version of it. I will advice you to be
    careful about running it though, check what else is in the archive first.
    Does it include files like libraries or fonts, if this is the case, it
    may require these to run. The file may also need other files that only
    are present in the archive. The worst case scenario is that it crashes
    your Amiga or do other nasty things to it.

If the internal checking was not succesful, AnArchiver will Launch either
Multiview or IDer for viewing the file, this depends upon whether you have
"Use MultiView only" enabled or not in the @{"Extract & View" link ExAndViewOptions} section of the
@{"AnArchiver Options" link AnArchOptions} window.


  @{b}- Deleting the file -@{ub}
After the file has been viewed, it will in most cases be automatically
deleted. There are however some exceptions: archives will only be deleted
when you quit AnArchiver and other files might be still be in use by other
programs.
If you wish to manually delete temporarely extracted files, it can be done
by using the @{"Delete Temporary Files" link DelTempFilesWin} window which can be started from the
"Misc" menu in the AnArchiver main Gui. 

@endnode








@node Limitations "Limitations of the Archivers"

  @{b}- Limitations -@{ub}

The Archivers have the following limitations:

 * Path names are limited to a maximum 255 characters in length.

 * The size of a single archive must not exceed 2 Gigabytes.

 * The maximum number of files that can be compressed in one invocation
   is limited only by available memory.

@endnode


@node Problems

  @{b}- Problems with LhA 2.1 -@{ub}

There are some problems with this version of LhA:

 * It crashes my Amiga when using the "CLI Window" Output option (which can
   be set in the @{"Misc Options" link MiscOptions} section of the @{"AnArchiver Options" link AnArchOptions} window), but
   it works fine when using GUI output. It seems like there is no problems
   as long as the output is re-directed to somewhere else than the standard
   console. So if you are using LhA version 2.1 with AnArchiver, my advice
   is to use "GUI Window" output only. There also used to be problems with
   using quiet output (by setting the Output option to "Off (Quiet)" ), but
   since this is fixed in version 1.5 of AnArchiver,  it means that it is
   also safe to use this option now.
   
 * When I use the "Full File Paths" option when adding files to an archive,
   LhA does not seem to check if the files already exists. This means that
   all selected files will be added even if they already exists in the
   archive, leading to the chance of there being duplicate files in it.



  @{b}- The Command Line Lenght Problem -@{ub}

Command line lenght limitations of the Archivers.

There is a limitation of how long the Archivers command line can be, if it's
too long, they will return a error message. This can happen if a lot of files
are specified on the command line or if the files have long path-names.

The solution AnArchiver uses to solve this problem with LZX is the following:
If the user selects a lot of files which would make the command line lenght
too long, AnArchiver will run the Archiver several times instead, and in each
turn, it will take as many file names in the command line as possible.
Everything will happen automatically, but you will be notified about it if you
have the "Show 'Adding/Deleting in X turns'" option enabled (which can be set
in the @{"AnArchiver Settings" link SettingsWindow} window).

With XAD the solution is the following:
I could have solved the problem by using exactly the same method as with LZX,
but I have found an alternative method instead. When extracting files from
archives by using the xadUnFile command, AnArchiver will force this command
to take it's input (of files to extract) from the output of another program.
But there are still one little problem: only a maximum of 127 files can be
extracted in one turn, if more files than 127 should be extracted, xadUnFile
would still have to be run more than one time.

When it comes to LhA and Zip, they both support methods that will be used by
AnArchiver for avoiding this limitation, so there are no problems with them.
This means that LhA and Zip only have to be run one time in order to Add or
Delete (and in LhA's case - also Extract) all selected files to/from the
archive.

Please Note! If you want to extract ALL files from the archive, there will be
no problems because no files will be specified on the command line. This will
instruct the Archivers to act upon ALL files in the selected archive instead.
When you want to delete ALL files from the archive,  AnArchiver will delete
the entire archive instead (after asking you first). For adding ALL files in
the source directory to an archive, AnArchiver will cd to the source dir and
use the "#?" wildcard combination (which matches ALL files) instead of passing
the name of every selected file/dir to the Archiver.



  @{b}- The "Minus" Problem -@{ub}

There are problems when trying to add files that have filenames that begins
with a minus (-) character in front of them to an archive, this is because
the Archivers use this character in front of their option names. This means
that filenames starting with a "-" (like this: -File.iff) will be considered
to be option switches by the LhA, LZX and Zip Archivers.

This problem is now solved with ALL Archivers in version 1.5 of AnArchiver.



  @{b}- The Wildcard Problem -@{ub}

Problems with Wildcard Characters (`()#?~%|*').

There are some problems when adding, extracting or deleting files which have
these characters in the file names to/from an archive because they are used
for wildcard matching.

This problem is now solved with ALL Archivers in version 1.5 of AnArchiver,
but I will still recommend that you don't use these characters in file names
(and certainly NOT in directory names!).



  @{b}- The "#?" Problem -@{ub}

When AnArchiver uses "#?" to add ALL files in the "Add files listview". 

If you select ALL files and dirs in the listview, AnArchiver will cd to the
Source directory and use the "#?" wildcard combination instead of passing
the name of every selected file/dir to the Archiver. This will speed up
things a little when adding a lot of files to LZX archives, since every
thing will be done in one turn only.

There are however, one little problem you should be aware of:
If you turn the "Recurse Sub-dirs" option off, things will work in a
different way than it would with this option on.

If you select absolutely everything in the listview (so that #? wildcard
matching will be used), the contents of selected dirs will NOT be added,
but if only some of the files/dirs in the lv. was selected, the contents
of the dirs would be added (not sub-dirs in the selected dirs though).

Please Note! The above problem is ONLY about when you turn the "Recurse
Sub-dirs" option OFF!


I was not sure about if I should include this function or not, since I know
that some users may find it confusing, but I feel that it was too important
to be left out, so I decided to include it anyway.

Personally, I always have the "Recurse Sub-dirs" option turned on, and only
in very rare occations I turn it off.
The reason for this, is that I think it's better to find out later that some
extra files was included, than it is to find out that not everything was
included as planned to the archive. 

@endnode


@node Archive2Use "What Archive format to use"

  @{b}- What Archive format to use -@{ub}

What Archive format you should use depends a lot on what you want to do with
the archives that you create, if it's for your own personal use, it usually
doesn't matter what you choose, but if they are intended for other people,
there are some things you should be aware of:


  @{b}- LhA -@{ub}
This is the most used archive format on the Amiga platform and as an example,
almost all archive files located on Aminet are in the LhA format, so if your
archive is mainly meant to be decomressed by other Amiga owners, LhA is the
best format to use. But if you want to make sure that also users of other
systems like Windows should have the ability to decompress your archives,
it is probably best to use the Zip format instead.


  @{b}- LZX -@{ub}
The biggest advantage of LZX is the compression methods it uses, this can
result in much smaller archives when compared to LhA and Zip archives, but
the bad thing about LZX is that it is an Amiga only format. Versions of the
LZX Archiver does not exist on other operating systems (the exception is the
MS-DOS version with extract support only that can be found on Aminet).
So it's best to use LZX when archive file size is of BIG importance and the
archive is ONLY meant to be decompressed by other Amiga (or UAE) users.


  @{b}- Zip -@{ub}
Zip is the most used archive format on PC's that are running Windows, which
in turn means that it is the most used archive format of them all, this also
means that all Archive utilities, regardless of what platform it was made on,
should have Zip support included (well, at least in my opinion it does).
So if you want to make sure that your archives can be easily extracted by
everybody regardless of what OS he/she/it uses, you should use the Zip format.

The stuff mentioned above is the main reason why I included Zip support in
AnArchiver.

@endnode


@node PrgInformasjon "Program Information"

   @{b}- Program Information -@{ub}

AnArchiver was made by using D. Keletsekis's Gui4Cli 3.8.
Gui4Cli is an easy scripted language for creating & running GUIs.
If you want to get hold of the whole package for making your own ones,
it can be found :

  - on AmiNet, under Dev/Gui/Gui4Cli.lha, or 
  - at D. Keletsekis's web page, http://users.hol.gr/~dck/gcmain.htm


